%%TITLE
Brush cytology for the detection of high-risk HPV infection in oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma.
%%ABSTRACT
High-risk human papillomavirus (HR-HPV) infection is associated with improved prognosis and a better response to treatment in patients with oropharyngeal squamous cell carcinoma (OPSCC). Brush cytology is a noninvasive method with which to collect cells from the surface of mucosal lesions. The objective of the current study was to assess the performance of OPSCC brush cytology for the detection of HR-HPV.Liquid-based brush cytology specimens were prospectively collected during panendoscopy from 51 patients with OPSCC. Cell suspensions were analyzed with Papanicolaou staining, polymerase chain reaction-based HPV DNA testing, and p16 immunostaining. HPV testing and p16 staining were also performed on paired OPSCC biopsy or surgical resection specimens. The detection of HR-HPV DNA alone and the combined positivity for HR-HPV DNA and p16 protein in dysplastic squamous cells were used to calculate accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, and positive and negative predictive values for HR-HPV detection using brush cytology samples.Approximately 96% of OPSCC brush cytology samples (49 of 51 samples) were classified as satisfactory for evaluation. Dysplastic squamous cells were found in 88% of samples (43 of 49 samples). HPV DNA testing was conclusive in 95% of samples (41 of 43 samples) and revealed HR-HPV DNA in approximately 54% of patients (22 of 41 patients) (HPV type 16 in 19 patients and HPV type 33 in 3 patients). Approximately 49% of brush cytology samples (20 of 41 samples) were positive for HR-HPV DNA and p16 expression. The accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, positive predictive value, and negative predictive value of brush cytology to identify HR-HPV DNA-positive and p16-positive OPSCC samples were 88%, 83%, 94%, 95%, and 81%, respectively.Brush cytology appears to be a valid approach with which to determine the HR-HPV status of patients with OPSCC.
%%MATERIALS AND METHODS
Patient Selection
Patients with OPSCC referred to the Department of Otorhinolaryngology, Head and Neck Surgery at Kant- onsspital St. Gallen were asked to participate in the study. Written informed consent was obtained from each patient. The study protocol was approved by the local ethics committee.
Brush Cytology Specimens
Brush cytology samples were collected from visible lesions of the oropharyngeal region during panendoscopy. Brush
heads (Cytobrush Plus GT; CooperSurgical Inc, Trum- bull, CT) were rotated on the lesional surface several times and transferred into methanol-based preservative solution (ThinPrep Solution; Hologic Suisse, Lausanne, Switzer- land). An aliquot of each sample was processed with liquid-based technology (ThinPrep 5000 Processor; Hologic), stained using the Papanicolaou method, and evaluated by a board-certified cytopathologist (R.S.) for cellularity and adequacy for evaluation using the catego- ries “satisfactory” or “unsatisfactory.” Specimens with
>5000 squamous cells were classified as satisfactory for
evaluation and further categorized as “negative” or “positive” for dysplastic squamous cells using the criteria of the Bethesda System.
Histopathological Analysis
Biopsy and surgical resection specimens were fixed in neutral-buffered formalin (4%) and processed for histo- logical analysis using standard methods. Diagnostic evalu- ation of hematoxylin and eosin-stained tissue sections was performed by experienced board-certified pathologists blinded against the HPV status of the OPSCC sample. Carcinomas were classified according to the World Health Organization classification system for head and neck tumors.13
p16 Staining
Formalin-fixed and paraffin-embedded tissue sections measuring 3 lm in thickness were deparaffinized followed by antigen retrieval (ethylenediaminetetraacetic acid [pH 9.0] at 958C for 30 minutes). p16 staining (clone E6H4 [dilution 1:10] for 30 minutes; MTM Laboratories, Hei- delberg, Germany) was performed on a Leica BOND- MAX instrument (Leica Biosystems, Nussloch, Germany) using the Bond Polymer Refine detection kit (Leica). Antigen retrieval was omitted for p16 staining of brush cytology samples.
For both biopsy and surgical resection specimens, p16 positivity was defined as 270% tumor cells with strong nuclear and cytoplasmic staining.14 Brush cytology samples were scored positive if there were >10 dysplastic squamous cells (isolated or in groups) with strong p16 staining to avoid false-positive scoring results.
DNA Extraction
Genomic DNA was prepared from 3 to 5 tissue sections measuring 4 lm in thickness after manual

microdissection of tumor cells. After deparaffinization, proteinase K digestion was performed overnight in 100 lL of extraction buffer (50 mM of potassium chloride, 10 mM of Tris [pH 8.3], 0.045% Tween, 0.08% NP-40,
and 0.1 mg/mL of gelatin) at 608C. After centrifugation, whole lysis extract was used for PCR analysis.
For brush cytology specimens, 1 mL of the cell sus- pension was centrifuged for 10 minutes at 10,000 revolu- tions per minute. After removing the supernatant fluid, digestion of the cell pellet was performed as for dissected tumor cells.
HPV Detection
HPV DNA was detected by PCR amplification using the L1C1/L1C2 consensus primer set, which targets the highly conserved L1 region of the HPV genome und pro- duces amplicons of approximately 250 base pairs.15 PCR reactions were performed in a final volume of 40 lL con- sisting of 2 lL of DNA extract as a template, 13 PCR buffer (Sigma-Aldrich, Buchs, Switzerland), 10 pmol of forward and reverse primer, 0.25 mM of dNTPs (Sigma- Aldrich), and 1.25 U of JumpStart Taq DNA Polymerase (Sigma-Aldrich). The final concentration of magnesium
chloride was 1.5 mM. L1C1/2 PCR was performed in a Biometra T3000 thermocycler (Labgene Scientific, Chatel-St-Denis, Switzerland) using the following pro- gram: preheating for 2 minutes at 958C followed by 5 cycles of 30 seconds at 948C, 20 seconds at 438C, and 30 seconds at 728C; another 40 cycles of 30 seconds at 948C, 20 seconds at 488C, and 30 seconds at 728C; and a final extension of 5 minutes at 728C. Five lL of each PCR product were analyzed by gel electrophoresis on a 2% agarose gel containing Biotium GelRed dye (Chemie Brunschwig, Basel, Switzerland). PCR products with a specific amplicon were purified using the Qiagen PCR Purification Kit (Qiagen Instruments AG, Hombrechti- kon, Switzerland). Negative and positive controls were included in each HPV PCR run. To rule out false- negative results, b-globin PCR was performed for samples with negative HPV PCR to test for effective DNA extrac- tion and DNA integrity. Only samples with amplifiable DNA were scored as negative for HPV.
Direct sequencing of purified PCR products was
performed by automated capillary electrophoresis on the ABI PRISM 3130 Genetic Analyzer instrument (Thermo Fisher Scientific AG, Reinach, Switzerland) using the L1C1 primer and the BigDye Terminator v1.1 Cycle Sequencing Kit (Thermo Fisher Scientific AG). The HPV genotype was determined by sequence similarity analysis using the National Center for Biotechnology Information Basic Local Alignment Search Tool (BLAST) with the GenBank databank. The HPV genotype was identified based on the degree of identity between the query and matched sequences using “100% identity” as criterion for genotyping except for variants not recorded in the Gen- Bank. If the presence of overlapping base-calling peaks on the computer-generated electropherogram suggested
infection with >1 HPV genotype, the secondary sequence
was identified by manual base calling and used for sequence similarity analysis as described.
Statistical Analysis
Data were analyzed with descriptive statistics using the SPSS Statistics 22 software (IBM Corporation, Armonk NY). Two endpoints were used for the comparative evalu- ation: HR-HPV DNA positivity and positive HR-HPV status. Positive HR-HPV status was defined as PCR- based detection of HR-HPV DNA in combination with positive p16 staining.5,7,8 The diagnostic performance of brush cytology specimens was evaluated by calculating the
